<subSubSection pageId="117" pageNumber="118" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="117.[151,1437,1177,2032]" pageId="117" pageNumber="118">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,294,1682,1708]" pageId="117" pageNumber="118">Ecology</emphasis>
. Intertidal and shallow subtidal, known depth range: 
<quantity box="[894,983,1682,1708]" metricMagnitude="1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" metricValueMax="2.0" metricValueMin="0.0" pageId="117" pageNumber="118" unit="m" value="10.0" valueMax="20.0" valueMin="0.0">0–20 m</quantity>
; rocky shores and reefs, under boulders, also in coral rocks and on “sand and shell bottoms” in deeper water (
<bibRefCitation author="Haig, J." box="[920,1042,1718,1744]" pageId="117" pageNumber="118" pagination="1 - 440" refId="ref72816" refString="Haig, J. (1960) The Porcellanidae (Crustacea: Anomura) of the Eastern Pacific. Allan Hancock Pacific Expedition, 24, 1 - 440." type="journal article" year="1960">Haig 1960</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Gore, R. H." box="[1054,1177,1718,1744]" pageId="117" pageNumber="118" pagination="1 - 34" refId="ref72204" refString="Gore, R. H. (1982) Porcellanid crabs from the coasts of Mexico and Central America (Crustacea: Decapoda: Anomura). Smithsonian Contributions to Zoology, 363, 1 - 34. https: // doi. org / 10.5479 / si. 00810282.363" type="journal article" year="1982">Gore 1982</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="117" pageNumber="118" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="117.[151,1437,1177,2032]" pageId="117" pageNumber="118">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,308,1754,1780]" pageId="117" pageNumber="118">Remarks</emphasis>
. Despite having a wide distribution in the tropical eastern Pacific (
<typeStatus box="[1062,1112,1754,1780]" pageId="117" pageNumber="118">type</typeStatus>
locality: Galápagos) and the Caribbean Sea, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Haig" authorityYear="1960" box="[330,463,1791,1816]" class="Malacostraca" family="Porcellanidae" genus="Petrolisthes" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="117" pageNumber="118" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tonsorius">
<emphasis box="[330,463,1791,1816]" italics="true" pageId="117" pageNumber="118">P. tonsorius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
does not appear to be a common species. Although 
<bibRefCitation author="Hiller, A. &amp; Werding, B." box="[1059,1341,1790,1816]" pageId="117" pageNumber="118" pagination="143 - 151" refId="ref73734" refString="Hiller, A. &amp; Werding, B. (2019) A new species of Petrolisthes (Crustacea, Anomura, Porcellanidae) inhabiting vermetid formations (Mollusca, Gastropoda, Vermetidae) in the southern Caribbean Sea. ZooKeys, 876, 143 - 151. https: // doi. org / 10.3897 / zookeys. 876.37244" type="journal article" year="2019">Hiller &amp; Werding (2019)</bibRefCitation>
seem to have confirmed the status of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Haig" authorityYear="1960" box="[483,617,1827,1852]" class="Malacostraca" family="Porcellanidae" genus="Petrolisthes" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="117" pageNumber="118" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tonsorius">
<emphasis box="[483,617,1827,1852]" italics="true" pageId="117" pageNumber="118">P. tonsorius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as a single species with transisthmian distribution, the average distance between the populations from the eastern Pacific and western Atlantic in the 16S rRNA gene fragment was 4.8%, which is rather significant (see also 
<bibRefCitation author="Hiller, A. &amp; Kraus, H. &amp; Almon, M. &amp; Werding, B." box="[550,744,1898,1924]" pageId="117" pageNumber="118" pagination="547 - 569" refId="ref73577" refString="Hiller, A., Kraus, H., Almon, M. &amp; Werding, B. (2006) The Petrolisthes galathinus complex: species boundaries based on color pattern, morphology and molecules, and evolutionary interrelationships between the complex and other Porcellanidae (Crustacea: Decapoda: Anomura). Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution, 40, 547 - 569. https: // doi. org / 10.1016 / j. ympev. 2006.03.030" type="journal article" year="2006">
Hiller 
<emphasis box="[622,671,1898,1924]" italics="true" pageId="117" pageNumber="118">et al</emphasis>
. 2006
</bibRefCitation>
: fig. 3). They also noted an overlapping intraspecific variation in the colour pattern on each side of the Isthmus of 
<collectingCountry box="[738,830,1934,1960]" name="Panama" pageId="117" pageNumber="118">Panama</collectingCountry>
, with the more common brown colour morph and the less common bluish colour morph (
<figureCitation box="[543,635,1970,1996]" captionStart="FIGURE 73" captionStartId="118.[151,250,948,972]" captionTargetBox="[258,1329,181,924]" captionTargetId="figure-23@118.[258,1329,181,924]" captionTargetPageId="118" captionText="FIGURE 73. Petrolisthes tonsorius Haig, 1960: extra-limital specimen, male (cl cw indet.) from Saint Martin (FLMNH UF 31931), dorsal view, right P1 and P2 missing [photograph courtesy of Gustav Paulay / François Michonneau]." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5532394" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5532394/files/figure.png" pageId="117" pageNumber="118">
Figs. 
<geoCoordinate box="[605,635,1970,1996]" degrees="73, 90" direction="east" orientation="longitude" pageId="117" pageNumber="118" precision="555" value="73.9">73</geoCoordinate>
</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[646,695,1970,1996]" captionStart="FIGURE 90" captionStartId="140.[151,250,1624,1648]" captionTargetBox="[164,1424,181,1599]" captionTargetId="figure-19@140.[164,1424,181,1601]" captionTargetPageId="140" captionText="FIGURE 90. Some western Atlantic Porcellanidae (all species reported from Panama or Golfo de Urabá at the Panamanian- Colombian border) photographed in situ: A, Neopisosoma angustifrons (Benedict, 1901), Golfo de Urabá, Colombia; B, Neopisosoma neglectum Werding, 1986, Golfo de Urabá, Colombia; C, Pachycheles tuerkayi Werding &amp; Hiller, 2017, Santa Marta, Colombia; D, Petrolisthes jugosus Streets, 1872, Tayrona, Colombia; E, Petrolisthes tonsorius Haig, 1960, blue colour morph, Bonaire; F, Petrolisthes quadratus Benedict, 1901, Bonaire [photographs courtesy of Juan-Felipe Lazarus-Agudelo (A–D) and Marco Faasse (E, F)]." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5532436" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5532436/files/figure.png" pageId="117" pageNumber="118">90E</figureCitation>
; see also 
<bibRefCitation author="Garcia-Madrigal, M. S. &amp; Andreu-Sanchez, L. I." box="[798,1269,1970,1996]" pageId="117" pageNumber="118" pagination="23 - 54" refId="ref71705" refString="Garcia-Madrigal, M. S. &amp; Andreu-Sanchez, L. I. (2009) Los cangrejos porcelanidos (Decapoda: Anomura) del Pacifico sur de Mexico, incluyendo una lista y clave de identificacion para todas las especies del Pacifico oriental tropical. Ciencia y Mar, 13 (39), 23 - 54." type="journal article" year="2009">García-Madrigal &amp; Andréu-Sánchez 2009</bibRefCitation>
: fig. 5D; 
<bibRefCitation author="Hiller, A. &amp; Werding, B." pageId="117" pageNumber="118" pagination="143 - 151" refId="ref73734" refString="Hiller, A. &amp; Werding, B. (2019) A new species of Petrolisthes (Crustacea, Anomura, Porcellanidae) inhabiting vermetid formations (Mollusca, Gastropoda, Vermetidae) in the southern Caribbean Sea. ZooKeys, 876, 143 - 151. https: // doi. org / 10.3897 / zookeys. 876.37244" type="journal article" year="2019">Hiller &amp; Werding 2019</bibRefCitation>
: fig. 1).
</paragraph>
